## Quick Start

### Prerequisites

- Python 3.12+
- [uv](https://docs.astral.sh/uv/) package manager

```bash
# Install uv (if not already installed)
curl -LsSf https://astral.sh/uv/install.sh | sh
```

### Setup

```bash
git clone <repository-url>
cd {{ project_name }}
uv sync                    # Install all dependencies
uv run pytest              # Verify everything works
```

### Running Code

```bash
# Run scripts
uv run python scripts/generate_data.py
uv run python scripts/analyze_data.py

# Run tests
uv run pytest tests/ -v

# Start Jupyter
uv run jupyter notebook
```

## DrWatson-Style Data Management

This project includes `drwatson.py`, which provides Julia's DrWatson.jl-style
utilities for reproducible scientific computing in Python.

### Path Management

```python
from {{ package_name }} import datadir, plotsdir, datafile, savename

# Get directory paths (always relative to project root)
datadir()              # -> Path("<project>/data")
plotsdir()             # -> Path("<project>/plots")

# Get file paths
datafile("results.h5") # -> Path("<project>/data/results.h5")

# Create deterministic filenames from parameters
params = {"alpha": 0.5, "N": 100, "method": "euler"}
savename(params, "h5")
# -> "N=100_alpha=0.5_method=euler.h5"
```

### Saving & Loading Data (HDF5)

```python
from {{ package_name }} import save_data, load_data, load_selective
import numpy as np

# Save data with automatic metadata (git commit, timestamp)
data = {
    "temperature": np.random.randn(1000),
    "pressure": np.random.randn(1000),
}
save_data(data, "experiment_001", metadata={"run": 1, "sensor": "A"})

# Load everything
result = load_data("experiment_001")
print(result["temperature"])
print(result["_metadata"])  # Includes git info, timestamp, custom metadata

# Load only specific datasets
partial = load_selective("experiment_001", keys=["temperature"])
```

### Smart Caching with `produce_or_load`

```python
from {{ package_name }} import produce_or_load

def expensive_simulation(params):
    """Run a computationally expensive simulation."""
    # ... your simulation code ...
    return {"result": computed_data}

params = {"N": 1000, "dt": 0.01}

# First call: runs the simulation, saves result to data/
# Second call: loads cached result (no recomputation)
data, filepath = produce_or_load(expensive_simulation, params)
```

## Development

